elements.title: defend the European 400-metres title
elements.contents: ... that Libania Grenot was the first woman in three decades to successfully defend the European 400-metres title (final pictured)?

elements.title: Captain James Cook
elements.contents: ... that Captain James Cook and his crew were some of the first Europeans to witness and record Polynesians surfing?

elements.title: Hanahaki disease
elements.contents: ... that Hanahaki disease, a fictional illness in which a person coughs up flowers due to unrequited love, is often used in queer fan fiction to symbolize repressed desire?

elements.title: Carmel Naughton
elements.contents: ... that Carmel Naughton, having been told that girls were "stupid and couldn't do maths", sponsored a STEM scholarship fund?

elements.title: Samuel Freeman House
elements.contents: ... that after moving into the Samuel Freeman House, the owners sat on cardboard boxes because they could not afford real furniture?

elements.title: Gabriel Rucker
elements.contents: ... that Nicolas Cage was trained by award-winning chef Gabriel Rucker for one of his films?

elements.title: a Nevada TV station
elements.contents: ... that a subcontractor working on the tower of a Nevada TV station recorded footage of the PEPCON disaster as it unfolded nearby?

elements.title: Maude Simmons
elements.contents: ... that Maude Simmons played the mother of Paul Robeson on stage and the mother of Sidney Poitier on screen?

elements.title: rice riots of 1918
elements.contents: ... that the Japanese government responded to the rice riots of 1918, which involved up to 10 million participants, with a "candy and whip" policy?
